# Bluebookers Room Sync — WebSocket Server

Pushes live room updates (status, type, price, number, cleaning/maintenance
state) AND live reservation updates (guest name, check-in/check-out dates,
booking status — including checkout) between every open Layout and
Calendar tab. This is a separate, small Node.js process that runs
alongside your existing PHP/Apache/MySQL (XAMPP) stack — it does not
replace or modify how PHP serves pages, it just watches the `rooms` and
`reservations` tables and tells connected browser tabs when something
changes.

**This is real infrastructure, not just a code change.** It requires
installing Node.js and keeping this process running continuously
(typically as a background service), separate from your web server.
Read this whole file before deploying.

## What it does

- Connects to your existing MySQL database (same one PHP uses).
- Every ~1.5 seconds (configurable), checks whether any row in the
  `rooms` table changed since the last check, and separately whether
  any *active* reservation (or one that just changed status) is new or
  different since the last check.
- If something changed, pushes the new data to every connected browser
  tab over a WebSocket connection — as a `rooms_changed` message for
  room-level changes, or a `reservations_changed` message for guest
  name / dates / booking-status changes.
- Both Layout pages and the Calendar page connect to this server and
  update their own DOM in place when a message arrives — no page
  reload. On Calendar, a reservation transitioning to `checked_out`
  removes its bar entirely rather than just restyling it.

It does **not** receive "something changed" events from PHP directly. It
polls the database itself, so any change to either table — from Layout,
from Calendar, from a future feature, or from a direct DB edit — gets
picked up automatically, with no PHP write-path needing to remember to
notify it.

The `reservations` table is never pruned (bookings are kept as a
permanent record), so unlike `rooms` it isn't polled/diffed in full each
cycle — only reservations that are currently active (reserved/checked
in) or changed within the last minute are considered. This keeps the
poll cheap regardless of how many bookings accumulate over time.

## 1. Install Node.js

If you don't already have it: download the LTS installer from
https://nodejs.org and run it. Verify with:

```
node --version
npm --version
```

## 2. Install dependencies

From this folder (`ws-server/`):

```
npm install
```

This installs `ws` (WebSocket server), `mysql2` (database client), and
`dotenv` (config loading).

## 3. Configure

Copy `.env.example` to `.env` and fill in your real database credentials
— the same ones your PHP app's `config.php` uses (`DB_HOST`, `DB_NAME`,
`DB_USER`, `DB_PASS`). Leave `WS_PORT` at `8081` unless that port is
already in use on your server, in which case pick another and update it
in the two browser-side files mentioned in step 5.

## 4. Run it

For a first test, run it in the foreground so you can see its log
output and confirm it connects:

```
node server.js
```

You should see:
```
[ws-server] listening on ws://0.0.0.0:8081
[ws-server] primed snapshot with N room(s)
```

If you see a database connection error instead, double-check `.env`.

Press Ctrl+C to stop it. For real use, it needs to stay running
continuously, which means running it as a background service rather
than a terminal window you have to keep open:

**Windows (XAMPP is commonly run on Windows):**
- Easiest: install [PM2](https://pm2.keymetrics.io/) (`npm install -g pm2`),
  then `pm2 start server.js --name room-sync` and `pm2 save`. Use
  `pm2-startup` (or `pm2-windows-startup`) so it survives a reboot.
- Alternative: [NSSM](https://nssm.cc/) to register `node server.js` as
  a proper Windows service.

**Linux/macOS:**
- `pm2 start server.js --name room-sync && pm2 save && pm2 startup`, or
- a systemd unit file running `node server.js` with `Restart=always`.

## 5. Point the browser clients at it

Both `assets/js/calendar.js` and the new `assets/js/realtime-room-sync.js`
(included by the Layout pages) connect to:

```
ws://<page's own hostname>:8081
```

by default — it infers the hostname from whatever the browser already
loaded the page from, so this works out of the box for `localhost`, a
LAN IP, or a real domain, as long as the port matches `WS_PORT` in your
`.env`. If you changed `WS_PORT`, update the matching `WS_PORT` constant
near the top of both `calendar.js` (search for `BB_WS_PORT`) and
`realtime-room-sync.js`.

If your site is served over HTTPS, browsers will block a plain `ws://`
connection from a secure page — you'll need `wss://` instead, which
means putting this server behind a reverse proxy (nginx/Apache/IIS) that
terminates TLS and forwards to `ws://localhost:8081`, or adding TLS
directly in `server.js` via Node's `https` module. This isn't set up
out of the box since it depends on your existing certificate setup.

## Security note

This first version has no authentication on the WebSocket connection
itself — anyone who can reach the port can see everything broadcast:
room status/type/price/number changes, and for active reservations,
guest name and stay dates (contact info, email, address, payment, and
other reservation fields are *not* broadcast — only what the floor-plan
card and calendar bar already display). For a production deployment
reachable beyond your own LAN, consider: restricting the port via
firewall to your server's own network, adding a shared-secret token
check in the WebSocket handshake, and the `wss://` (TLS) setup mentioned
above.

## Known limitations (not solved by this layer)

- **Floor reassignment**: which floor a room appears on in Layout is
  determined by hardcoded room-number lists in `layout.php` /
  `layout_1st_floor.php` / `layout_2nd_floor.php` (e.g. `$leftRooms =
  ['303','302','301']`), not a stored `floor` column. Renaming a room's
  number to one that belongs to a different floor's hardcoded list (or
  to no list at all) needs a manual code change to those files — this
  sync layer propagates the *data* change everywhere correctly, but
  it can't relocate a room between floor pages on its own.
- **No room visibility/active flag**: the schema has no "hidden,"
  "inactive," or similar column on `rooms` — every room that exists is
  shown everywhere there's a room list. Building a true room-hide
  feature would need a new schema column and changes to every
  room-listing query, which is a separate piece of work from the sync
  layer itself.